{"text": "number of sites, this allows to realize quantum superpo-\n\nsitions with the two classical Ising ground states at angle\n\n\u03b8 = \u03c0\u2212. (It is interesting to note that the term in \u03c3x\n\nj \u03c3x\n\nj+1\n\ndoes not alter the presence of the two edge modes as long\n\nas sin \u03b8 \u226a1.) The edge Majorana fermion at j = 1 can\n\nyet be related to a local spin observable\n\n\u03c3z\n\n1 =\n\n\u221a\n\n2\u03b11.\n\n(30)\n\nTo produce a delocalized qubit i.e. the \u03c4-spin, we can\n\nplace the system in a ring geometry with an adjustable\n\njunction.\n\nIn this way, in a ring geometry \u03c3\u03bc\n\n1 = \u03c3\u03bc\n\nN+1\n\nimply that\n\nei\u03c0 P\n\n1\u2264j\u2264N c\u2020\n\njcj =\n\nY\n\n1\u2264j\u2264N\n\nei\u03c0c\u2020\n\njcj = 1.\n\n(31)\n\nIn our case, c\u2020\n\njcj is related to the operator \u03c3y\n\nj = 2c\u2020\n\njcj \u2212\n\n1 = 2i\u03b1j\u03b7j. In a ring geometry, the string may allow\n\nthe phase to adjust in a way to account for the periodic\n\nboundary conditions. This is also equivalent to\n\nei\u03c0 P\n\n1\u2264j<N c\u2020\n\njcj =\n\nY\n\n1\u2264j<N\n\nei\u03c0c\u2020\n\njcj\n\n=\n\n\uf8eb\n\n\uf8edY\n\n1\u2264j\u2264N\n\nei\u03c0c\u2020\n\njcj\n\n\uf8f6\n\n\uf8f8\u00d7 ei\u03c0c\u2020\n\nNcN\n\n= (1 \u22122c\u2020\n\nNcN).\n\n(32)\n\nTherefore, we have the identities\n\n\u03c3x\n\nN\u03c3y\n\nN =\n\n\u221a\n\n2\u03b7Nei\u03c0 P\n\n1\u2264j<N c\u2020\n\njcj(2c\u2020\n\nNcN \u22121)\n\n=\n\n\u221a\n\n2\u03b7N(1 \u22122c\u2020\n\nNcN)(2c\u2020\n\nNcN \u22121)\n\n= \u2212\n\n\u221a\n\n2\u03b7N.\n\n(33)\n\nFor fermions (c\u2020\n\njcj)2 = c\u2020\n\njcj. Similarly,\n\n\u03c3z\n\n1\u03c3z\n\nN = \u03c3z\n\nN+1\u03c3z\n\nN =\n\n\u221a\n\n2\u03b11(1 \u22122c\u2020\n\nNcN)\n\n\u221a\n\n2\u03b1N\n\n= 2\u03b11(2i\u03b7N\u03b1N)\u03b1N = 2i\u03b11\u03b7N.\n\n(34)\n\nThis term can be implemented through a small time-\n\ndependent Ising coupling r\u2032\n\nz(t)\u03c3z\n\nN+1\u03c3z\n\nN between sites 1\n\nand N in a (small) ring geometry. When rz = r\u2032\n\nz > 0 this\n\ncorresponds to a chain with periodic boundary conditions\n\nand therefore there is no free Majorana fermions. The\n\noperator 2i\u03b7N\u03b11 = 2i\u03b7N\u03b1N+1 would remain equal to +1.\n\nIf now, we have a small amplitude r\u2032\n\nz(t) \u226arz this may in\n\nprinciple allow to address both signs of the interaction in\n\ntime while preserving the ground state in the bulk.", "embedding": [0.018318035, 0.013930936, 0.0077107577, 0.010258743, -0.0013016992, -0.023390926, -0.009690736, -0.018013632, -0.06275611, 0.0896425, 0.05107903, 0.008350394, 0.016269082, -0.03756867, -0.0351563, 0.032170087, -0.006854272, -0.04517804, -0.07001789, 0.021500802, 0.006034065, 0.008663756, -0.06173172, -0.0024616718, -0.028492723, 0.07047367, 0.013438934, 0.026425865, 0.057210304, 0.040076878, 0.025694024, -0.024010453, 0.008506322, -0.037633445, -0.023509143, 0.0055509955, 0.0066622524, -0.017432176, 0.032273762, -0.029392553, 0.03925075, -0.011270884, 0.015055193, -0.012645784, -0.041891064, 0.009986517, -0.007190007, 0.0011098854, -0.011469575, -0.0848933, -0.0008685814, -0.012616335, 0.053605333, 0.018316332, -0.02671142, -0.015984528, -0.0005627031, 0.01647802, -0.026941873, -0.02333696, 0.0062281657, -0.03279306, 0.0013780346, -0.07006579, 0.019708492, 0.028727915, 0.006546765, 0.03849944, -0.014835728, -0.06164124, -0.026547056, -0.03098518, -0.030427875, -0.025602624, -0.042275, 0.0153506845, -0.0106582865, -0.016300831, -0.07016911, -0.025552802, -0.013296848, -0.003178264, -0.034490317, 0.0007301164, -0.03621794, 0.006783373, -0.013430392, -0.02346975, 0.0021397995, -0.0050108493, 0.012407251, 0.03014724, 0.0073190904, 0.027368385, 0.04107446, 0.01679151, 0.0098225875, 0.0527732, 0.009145457, 0.009641243, -0.018895447, 0.056960814, 0.0074745263, 0.051523052, -0.04757716, 0.03309205, -0.0040364084, 0.017669864, -0.014893877, -0.03461677, 0.015724247, -0.025832701, 0.03726046, 0.04333155, 0.02418987, 0.023792766, -0.004